  "notes": {
    "greeting": "For You, John",
    "cards": [
      {
        "icon": "⏱",
        "title": "Understanding Tempo",
        "body": "The numbers next to exercises — e.g. 3-1-1 — describe the speed of each phase. The first number is the eccentric (lowering), the second is the pause at the bottom, the third is the concentric (lifting). A Back Squat at 3-1-1 means: 3 seconds down, 1 second pause, 1 second to stand up. This builds tendon and tissue resilience. Do not rush it."
      },
      {
        "icon": "📊",
        "title": "Understanding RPE",
        "body": "RPE stands for Rate of Perceived Exertion, on a scale of 1–10. RPE 7 means the weight is challenging but you could do 3 more reps if you had to. This is your target zone for strength work this month. You are not training to failure. If a set feels like RPE 9 or above, reduce the load slightly next set."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🦾",
        "title": "Priority Area This Month",
        "body": "The activation work at the start of each day is placed there deliberately — before any loading. Pay close attention to quality. If you feel any sharp sensation during pressing or rotational work, stop and flag it to your coach. Soreness the day after is normal. Pain during movement is not."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🏐",
        "title": "The Med Ball Work",
        "body": "The rotational slams on Day 3 are your first dedicated rotational power work. Use 2–3 kg only — the focus is speed of rotation, not load. Hips lead, trunk follows, arm releases. The same sequence as on court. Do not go heavier until the pattern feels automatic."
      },
      {
        "icon": "📅",
        "title": "Week 4 — Deload",
        "body": "Week 4 is a deload week. You will keep the same exercises and structure but reduce total sets by roughly 40% and remove the plyometrics entirely. This is not a rest week — it is a consolidation week. Your body adapts during recovery, not during the session itself."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🔁",
        "title": "Between Sessions",
        "body": "Aim for at least one rest day between each session. If you are playing on your off days, keep them low-to-moderate intensity in weeks 1–3. In week 4 you can push on court if you feel good — the training load in the gym is lower."
      }
    ]
  }
}